'''Banu Najjar''' (Arabic: بنو نجّار, "sons of the carpenter") or '''Banu al-Najjar''' is the name of several unrelated historical and modern-day tribes throughout the [[Arab world]]. The individual tribes vary in religious composition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yabeyrouth.com/8073-%D8%A2%D9%84-%D9%86%D8%AC%D9%91%D8%A7%D8%B1-2|access-date=20 October 2018|title=Banu Najjar}}</ref>
==In Islamic history== One Banu Najjar group is mentioned in the [[Constitution of Medina|Charter of Medina]], and the Banu Najjar of Medina were the maternal clan of Muhammad's grandfather [[Abdul-Muttalib]].<ref>{{cite journal|title= The Life, Work, and Character of Mohammed |last1=Power|first1=Edmond|journal= Studies: An Irish Quarterly Review |volume=3|issue=10|year=1914|pages=142–159}}</ref> Islamic historians like [[Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani]] and [[al-Tabari]] list them as a clan of the large [[Banu Khazraj]] tribe of Medina. Al-Asqalani states that their ancestor was Taymallah ibn Thalabah ibn Amr ibn al-Khazraj.<ref>Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani (1986). [[Fath al-Bari]]. page 144.</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The History of al-Tabari Vol. 6: Muhammad at Mecca|last1=al-Tabari|first1=Abu Jafar|page=125|isbn=9780887067075}}</ref> The Banu Najjar had at least three sub-clans.<ref name="Peters">{{cite book|title=The Arabs and Arabia on the Eve of Islam (Volume 3)|editor=FE Peters|pages=130–134, 153|chapter=Idol Worship in Pre-Islamic Medina|publisher=Routledge|year=2014|isbn=9781351894807}}</ref>
Before Islam, the Banu Najjar of Medina mainly practiced traditional Arab polytheism, and owned [[Cult image|idols]] named Samul, Husa, and at-Tamm that were destroyed after the clan converted to Islam.<ref name="Peters" /> They may have had a [[Mawla|tribal alliance]] with some of the Jews of Medina.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Guillaume|first1=Alfred|title=New light on the life of Muhammad|journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies|pages=427–428|volume=26|issue=2|year=1963}}</ref><ref name="Peters" />
Muhammad initially settled with them when he [[Hegira|emigrated]] from [[Mecca]] to Medina. The [[Al-Masjid an-Nabawi|Prophet's Mosque]] was later built in the tribe's garden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sunnah.com/bukhari/55/37|title=Sahih Bukhari|access-date=20 October 2018}}</ref> The Banu Najjar are praised in a hadith attributed to Muhammad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sunnah.com/bukhari/78/83|title=Sahih Bukhari|access-date=20 October 2018}}</ref>
